Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyReq.abstract:
The S3 location of the text file that contains the definition of the custom vocabulary. The URI must be in the same region as the API endpoint that you are calling. The general form is:

https://s3.<aws-region>.amazonaws.com/<AWSDOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET>/<keyprefix>/<objectkey>

For example:

https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/AWSDOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET/vocab.txt

For more information about S3 object names, see Object Keys in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

For more information about custom vocabularies, see Custom Vocabularies.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyReq.abstract: The name of the vocabulary to update. The name is case sensitive. If you try to update a vocabulary with the same name as a previous vocabulary you will receive a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyFil.name: vocabularyFilterFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyFil.abstract:
The Amazon S3 location of a text file used as input to create the vocabulary filter. Only use characters from the character set defined for custom vocabularies. For a list of character sets, see Character Sets for Custom Vocabularies.

The specified file must be less than 50 KB of UTF-8 characters.

If you provide the location of a list of words in the VocabularyFilterFileUri parameter, you can’t use the Words parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyFil.name: vocabularyFilterName
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyFil.abstract: The name of the vocabulary filter to update. If you try to update a vocabulary filter with the same name as another vocabulary filter, you get a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyFil.name: words
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyFil.abstract:
The words to use in the vocabulary filter. Only use characters from the character set defined for custom vocabularies. For a list of character sets, see Character Sets for Custom Vocabularies.

If you provide a list of words in the Words parameter, you can’t use the VocabularyFilterFileUri parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The language code for the language of the text file used to update the custom vocabulary. US English (en-US) is the only language supported in Amazon Transcribe Medical.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The date and time that the vocabulary was updated.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyState
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The processing state of the update to the vocabulary. When the VocabularyState field is READY, the vocabulary is ready to be used in a StartMedicalTranscriptionJob request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The language code of the language used for the entries in the updated vocabulary. U.S. English (en-US) is the only valid language code in Amazon Transcribe Medical.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.abstract:
The location in Amazon S3 of the text file that contains your custom vocabulary. The URI must be in the same Amazon Web Services Region as the resource that you are calling. The following is the format for a URI:

https://s3.<aws-region>.amazonaws.com/<bucket-name>/<keyprefix>/<objectkey>

For example:

https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/AWSDOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET/vocab.txt

For more information about Amazon S3 object names, see Object Keys in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

For more information about custom vocabularies in Amazon Transcribe Medical, see Medical Custom Vocabularies.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The name of the vocabulary to update. The name is case sensitive. If you try to update a vocabulary with the same name as a vocabulary you’ve already made, you get a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateCallAnalytics.name: categoryProperties
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateCallAnalytics.abstract: The attributes describing the analytics category. You can see information such as the rules that you’ve used to update the category and when the category was originally created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateCallAnalytics.name: categoryName
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateCallAnalytics.abstract: The name of the analytics category to update. The name is case sensitive. If you try to update a call analytics category with the same name as a previous category you will receive a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateCallAnalytics.name: rules
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateCallAnalytics.abstract: The rules used for the updated analytics category. The rules that you provide in this field replace the ones that are currently being used.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUntagResourceReques.name: resourceArn
Classes/AWSTranscribeUntagResourceReques.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the Amazon Transcribe resource you want to remove tags from. ARNs have the format arn:partition:service:region:account-id:resource-type/resource-id (for example, arn:aws:transcribe:us-east-1:account-id:transcription-job/your-job-name). Valid values for resource-type are: transcription-job, medical-transcription-job, vocabulary, medical-vocabulary, vocabulary-filter, and language-model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUntagResourceReques.name: tagKeys
Classes/AWSTranscribeUntagResourceReques.abstract: A list of tag keys you want to remove from a specified Amazon Transcribe resource.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: completionTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job was completed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: contentRedaction
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: The content redaction settings of the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: creationTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job was created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: If the TranscriptionJobStatus field is FAILED, a description of the error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: identifiedLanguageScore
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: A value between zero and one that Amazon Transcribe assigned to the language it identified in the source audio. A higher score indicates that Amazon Transcribe is more confident in the language it identified.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: identifyLanguage
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: Whether automatic language identification was enabled for a transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: The language code for the input speech.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: modelSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: The object used to call your custom language model to your transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: outputLocationType
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract:
Indicates the location of the output of the transcription job.

If the value is CUSTOMER_BUCKET then the location is the S3 bucket specified in the outputBucketName field when the transcription job was started with the StartTranscriptionJob operation.

If the value is SERVICE_BUCKET then the output is stored by Amazon Transcribe and can be retrieved using the URI in the GetTranscriptionJob response’s TranscriptFileUri field.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: startTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job started processing.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: transcriptionJobStatus
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: The status of the transcription job. When the status is COMPLETED, use the GetTranscriptionJob operation to get the results of the transcription.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: completionTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job completed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: contentRedaction
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: An object that describes content redaction settings for the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: creationTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job was created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract:
If the TranscriptionJobStatus field is FAILED, this field contains information about why the job failed.

The FailureReason field can contain one of the following values:

  • Unsupported media format - The media format specified in the MediaFormat field of the request isn’t valid. See the description of the MediaFormat field for a list of valid values.

  • The media format provided does not match the detected media format - The media format of the audio file doesn’t match the format specified in the MediaFormat field in the request. Check the media format of your media file and make sure that the two values match.

  • Invalid sample rate for audio file - The sample rate specified in the MediaSampleRateHertz of the request isn’t valid. The sample rate must be between 8,000 and 48,000 Hertz.

  • The sample rate provided does not match the detected sample rate - The sample rate in the audio file doesn’t match the sample rate specified in the MediaSampleRateHertz field in the request. Check the sample rate of your media file and make sure that the two values match.

  • Invalid file size: file size too large - The size of your audio file is larger than Amazon Transcribe can process. For more information, see Limits in the Amazon Transcribe Developer Guide.

  • Invalid number of channels: number of channels too large - Your audio contains more channels than Amazon Transcribe is configured to process. To request additional channels, see Amazon Transcribe Limits in the Amazon Web Services General Reference.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: identifiedLanguageScore
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: A value between zero and one that Amazon Transcribe assigned to the language that it identified in the source audio. Larger values indicate that Amazon Transcribe has higher confidence in the language it identified.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: identifyLanguage
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: A value that shows if automatic language identification was enabled for a transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: jobExecutionSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: Provides information about how a transcription job is executed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: The language code for the input speech.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: languageIdSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: Language-specific settings that can be specified when language identification is enabled for your transcription job. These settings include VocabularyName, VocabularyFilterName, and LanguageModelName.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: languageOptions
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: An object that shows the optional array of languages inputted for transcription jobs with automatic language identification enabled.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: media
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: An object that describes the input media for the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: mediaFormat
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: The format of the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: mediaSampleRateHertz
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: The sample rate, in Hertz (Hz), of the audio track in the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: modelSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: An object containing the details of your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: settings
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: Optional settings for the transcription job. Use these settings to turn on speaker recognition, to set the maximum number of speakers that should be identified and to specify a custom vocabulary to use when processing the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: startTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job started processing.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: subtitles
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: Generate subtitles for your batch transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: A key:value pair assigned to a given transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: transcript
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: An object that describes the output of the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: transcriptionJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: The name of the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: transcriptionJobStatus
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: The status of the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.name: absoluteTimeRange
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.abstract: A time range, set in seconds, between two points in the call.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.name: negate
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.abstract: If TRUE, the rule that you specify is applied to everything except for the phrases that you specify.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.name: participantRole
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.abstract: Determines whether the customer or the agent is speaking the phrases that you’ve specified.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.name: relativeTimeRange
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.abstract: An object that allows percentages to specify the proportion of the call where you would like to apply a filter. For example, you can specify the first half of the call. You can also specify the period of time between halfway through to three-quarters of the way through the call. Because the length of conversation can vary between calls, you can apply relative time ranges across all calls.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.name: targets
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.abstract: The phrases that you’re specifying for the transcript filter to match.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.name: transcriptFilterType
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptFilter.ht.abstract: Matches the phrase to the transcription output in a word for word fashion. For example, if you specify the phrase “I want to speak to the manager.” Amazon Transcribe attempts to match that specific phrase to the transcription.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscript.html#/c:.name: redactedTranscriptFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscript.html#/c:.abstract:
The S3 object location of the redacted transcript.

Use this URI to access the redacted transcript. If you specified an S3 bucket in the OutputBucketName field when you created the job, this is the URI of that bucket. If you chose to store the transcript in Amazon Transcribe, this is a shareable URL that provides secure access to that location.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscript.html#/c:.name: transcriptFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscript.html#/c:.abstract:
The S3 object location of the transcript.

Use this URI to access the transcript. If you specified an S3 bucket in the OutputBucketName field when you created the job, this is the URI of that bucket. If you chose to store the transcript in Amazon Transcribe, this is a shareable URL that provides secure access to that location.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTagResourceRequest..name: resourceArn
Classes/AWSTranscribeTagResourceRequest..abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the Amazon Transcribe resource you want to tag. ARNs have the format arn:partition:service:region:account-id:resource-type/resource-id (for example, arn:aws:transcribe:us-east-1:account-id:transcription-job/your-job-name). Valid values for resource-type are: transcription-job, medical-transcription-job, vocabulary, medical-vocabulary, vocabulary-filter, and language-model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTagResourceRequest..name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeTagResourceRequest..abstract: The tags you are assigning to a given Amazon Transcribe resource.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTag.html#/c:objc(cs.name: key
Classes/AWSTranscribeTag.html#/c:objc(cs.abstract: The first part of a key:value pair that forms a tag associated with a given resource. For example, in the tag ‘Department’:’Sales’, the key is ‘Department’.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTag.html#/c:objc(cs.name: value
Classes/AWSTranscribeTag.html#/c:objc(cs.abstract: The second part of a key:value pair that forms a tag associated with a given resource. For example, in the tag ‘Department’:’Sales’, the value is ‘Sales’.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitlesOutput.htm.name: formats
Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitlesOutput.htm.abstract: Specify the output format for your subtitle file; if you select both SRT and VTT formats, two output files are generated.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitlesOutput.htm.name: subtitleFileUris
Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitlesOutput.htm.abstract: Choose the output location for your subtitle file. This location must be an S3 bucket.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitles.html#/c:o.name: formats
Classes/AWSTranscribeSubtitles.html#/c:o.abstract: Specify the output format for your subtitle file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: transcriptionJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: An object containing details of the asynchronous transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: contentRedaction
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: An object that contains the request parameters for content redaction.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: identifyLanguage
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: Set this field to true to enable automatic language identification. Automatic language identification is disabled by default. You receive a BadRequestException error if you enter a value for a LanguageCode.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: jobExecutionSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: Provides information about how a transcription job is executed. Use this field to indicate that the job can be queued for deferred execution if the concurrency limit is reached and there are no slots available to immediately run the job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: KMSEncryptionContext
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: A map of plain text, non-secret key:value pairs, known as encryption context pairs, that provide an added layer of security for your data.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract:
The language code for the language used in the input media file.

To transcribe speech in Modern Standard Arabic (ar-SA), your audio or video file must be encoded at a sample rate of 16,000 Hz or higher.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: languageIdSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: The language identification settings associated with your transcription job. These settings include VocabularyName, VocabularyFilterName, and LanguageModelName.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: languageOptions
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract:
An object containing a list of languages that might be present in your collection of audio files. Automatic language identification chooses a language that best matches the source audio from that list.

To transcribe speech in Modern Standard Arabic (ar-SA), your audio or video file must be encoded at a sample rate of 16,000 Hz or higher.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: media
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: An object that describes the input media for a transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: mediaFormat
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: The format of the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: mediaSampleRateHertz
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract:
The sample rate, in Hertz, of the audio track in the input media file.

If you do not specify the media sample rate, Amazon Transcribe determines the sample rate. If you specify the sample rate, it must match the sample rate detected by Amazon Transcribe. In most cases, you should leave the MediaSampleRateHertz field blank and let Amazon Transcribe determine the sample rate.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: modelSettings
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: Choose the custom language model you use for your transcription job in this parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: outputBucketName
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract:
The location where the transcription is stored.

If you set the OutputBucketName, Amazon Transcribe puts the transcript in the specified S3 bucket. When you call the GetTranscriptionJob operation, the operation returns this location in the TranscriptFileUri field. If you enable content redaction, the redacted transcript appears in RedactedTranscriptFileUri. If you enable content redaction and choose to output an unredacted transcript, that transcript’s location still appears in the TranscriptFileUri. The S3 bucket must have permissions that allow Amazon Transcribe to put files in the bucket. For more information, see Permissions Required for IAM User Roles.

You can specify an Amazon Web Services Key Management Service (KMS) key to encrypt the output of your transcription using the OutputEncryptionKMSKeyId parameter. If you don’t specify a KMS key, Amazon Transcribe uses the default Amazon S3 key for server-side encryption of transcripts that are placed in your S3 bucket.

If you don’t set the OutputBucketName, Amazon Transcribe generates a pre-signed URL, a shareable URL that provides secure access to your transcription, and returns it in the TranscriptFileUri field. Use this URL to download the transcription.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: outputEncryptionKMSKeyId
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract:
The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the Amazon Web Services Key Management Service (KMS) key used to encrypt the output of the transcription job. The user calling the StartTranscriptionJob operation must have permission to use the specified KMS key.

You can use either of the following to identify a KMS key in the current account:

  • KMS Key ID: “1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab”

  • KMS Key Alias: “alias/ExampleAlias”

You can use either of the following to identify a KMS key in the current account or another account:

  • Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of a KMS Key: “arn:aws:kms:region:account ID:key/1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab”

  • ARN of a KMS Key Alias: “arn:aws:kms:region:account-ID:alias/ExampleAlias”

If you don’t specify an encryption key, the output of the transcription job is encrypted with the default Amazon S3 key (SSE-S3).

If you specify a KMS key to encrypt your output, you must also specify an output location in the OutputBucketName parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: outputKey
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract:
You can specify a location in an Amazon S3 bucket to store the output of your transcription job.

If you don’t specify an output key, Amazon Transcribe stores the output of your transcription job in the Amazon S3 bucket you specified. By default, the object key is “your-transcription-job-name.json”.

You can use output keys to specify the Amazon S3 prefix and file name of the transcription output. For example, specifying the Amazon S3 prefix, “folder1/folder2/”, as an output key would lead to the output being stored as “folder1/folder2/your-transcription-job-name.json”. If you specify “my-other-job-name.json” as the output key, the object key is changed to “my-other-job-name.json”. You can use an output key to change both the prefix and the file name, for example “folder/my-other-job-name.json”.

If you specify an output key, you must also specify an S3 bucket in the OutputBucketName parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: medicalTranscriptionJob

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: contentIdentificationType
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.abstract: You can configure Amazon Transcribe Medical to label content in the transcription output. If you specify PHI, Amazon Transcribe Medical labels the personal health information (PHI) that it identifies in the transcription output.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: KMSEncryptionContext
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.abstract: A map of plain text, non-secret key:value pairs, known as encryption context pairs, that provide an added layer of security for your data.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.abstract: The language code for the language spoken in the input media file. US English (en-US) is the valid value for medical transcription jobs. Any other value you enter for language code results in a BadRequestException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: media
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.abstract: Describes the input media file in a transcription request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: mediaFormat
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.abstract: The audio format of the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: mediaSampleRateHertz

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: medicalTranscriptionJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.abstract: The name of the medical transcription job. You can’t use the strings “.” or “..” by themselves as the job name. The name must also be unique within an Amazon Web Services account. If you try to create a medical transcription job with the same name as a previous medical transcription job, you get a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: outputBucketName
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.abstract:
The Amazon S3 location where the transcription is stored.

You must set OutputBucketName for Amazon Transcribe Medical to store the transcription results. Your transcript appears in the S3 location you specify. When you call the GetMedicalTranscriptionJob, the operation returns this location in the TranscriptFileUri field. The S3 bucket must have permissions that allow Amazon Transcribe Medical to put files in the bucket. For more information, see Permissions Required for IAM User Roles.

  • Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of a KMS key in the current account or another account: “arn:aws:kms:region:account-ID:key/1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab”

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: settings
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.abstract: Optional settings for the medical transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: specialty

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartMedicalTranscr.abstract: Add tags to an Amazon Transcribe medical transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.abstract: An object containing the details of the asynchronous call analytics job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.name: channelDefinitions
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.abstract: When you start a call analytics job, you must pass an array that maps the agent and the customer to specific audio channels. Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.name: dataAccessRoleArn
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of a role that has access to the S3 bucket that contains your input files. Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.name: media
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.abstract: Describes the input media file in a transcription request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.name: outputEncryptionKMSKeyId
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.abstract:
The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the Amazon Web Services Key Management Service key used to encrypt the output of the call analytics job. The user calling the operation must have permission to use the specified KMS key.

You use either of the following to identify an Amazon Web Services KMS key in the current account:

  • KMS Key ID: “1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab”

  • KMS Key Alias: “alias/ExampleAlias”

You can use either of the following to identify a KMS key in the current account or another account:

  • Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of a KMS key in the current account or another account: “arn:aws:kms:region:account ID:key/1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef1234567890ab”

  • ARN of a KMS Key Alias: “arn:aws:kms:region:accountID:alias/ExampleAlias”

If you don’t specify an encryption key, the output of the call analytics job is encrypted with the default Amazon S3 key (SSE-S3).

If you specify a KMS key to encrypt your output, you must also specify an output location in the OutputLocation parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.name: outputLocation
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.abstract:
The Amazon S3 location where the output of the call analytics job is stored. You can provide the following location types to store the output of call analytics job:

  • s3://DOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET1

    If you specify a bucket, Amazon Transcribe saves the output of the analytics job as a JSON file at the root level of the bucket.

  • s3://DOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET1/folder/

    f you specify a path, Amazon Transcribe saves the output of the analytics job as s3://DOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET1/folder/your-transcription-job-name.json.

    If you specify a folder, you must provide a trailing slash.

  • s3://DOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET1/folder/filename.json.

    If you provide a path that has the filename specified, Amazon Transcribe saves the output of the analytics job as s3://DOC-EXAMPLEBUCKET1/folder/filename.json.

You can specify an Amazon Web Services Key Management Service (KMS) key to encrypt the output of our analytics job using the OutputEncryptionKMSKeyId parameter. If you don’t specify a KMS key, Amazon Transcribe uses the default Amazon S3 key for server-side encryption of the analytics job output that is placed in your S3 bucket.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.name: settings
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartCallAnalyticsJ.abstract: A Settings object that provides optional settings for a call analytics job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: channelIdentification
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract:
Instructs Amazon Transcribe to process each audio channel separately and then merge the transcription output of each channel into a single transcription.

Amazon Transcribe also produces a transcription of each item detected on an audio channel, including the start time and end time of the item and alternative transcriptions of the item including the confidence that Amazon Transcribe has in the transcription.

You can’t set both ShowSpeakerLabels and ChannelIdentification in the same request. If you set both, your request returns a BadRequestException.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: maxAlternatives
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: The number of alternative transcriptions that the service should return. If you specify the MaxAlternatives field, you must set the ShowAlternatives field to true.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: maxSpeakerLabels
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: The maximum number of speakers to identify in the input audio. If there are more speakers in the audio than this number, multiple speakers are identified as a single speaker. If you specify the MaxSpeakerLabels field, you must set the ShowSpeakerLabels field to true.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: showAlternatives
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: Determines whether the transcription contains alternative transcriptions. If you set the ShowAlternatives field to true, you must also set the maximum number of alternatives to return in the MaxAlternatives field.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: showSpeakerLabels
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract:
Determines whether the transcription job uses speaker recognition to identify different speakers in the input audio. Speaker recognition labels individual speakers in the audio file. If you set the ShowSpeakerLabels field to true, you must also set the maximum number of speaker labels MaxSpeakerLabels field.

You can’t set both ShowSpeakerLabels and ChannelIdentification in the same request. If you set both, your request returns a BadRequestException.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: vocabularyFilterMethod
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: Set to mask to remove filtered text from the transcript and replace it with three asterisks (“***”) as placeholder text. Set to remove to remove filtered text from the transcript without using placeholder text. Set to tag to mark the word in the transcription output that matches the vocabulary filter. When you set the filter method to tag, the words matching your vocabulary filter are not masked or removed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: vocabularyFilterName
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: The name of the vocabulary filter to use when transcribing the audio. The filter that you specify must have the same language code as the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: The name of a vocabulary to use when processing the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSentimentFilter.htm.name: absoluteTimeRange
Classes/AWSTranscribeSentimentFilter.htm.abstract: The time range, measured in seconds, of the sentiment.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSentimentFilter.htm.name: negate

Classes/AWSTranscribeSentimentFilter.htm.name: participantRole

Classes/AWSTranscribeSentimentFilter.htm.name: relativeTimeRange

Classes/AWSTranscribeSentimentFilter.htm.name: sentiments

Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html#/c:objc(c.name: interruptionFilter
Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html#/c:objc(c.abstract: A condition for a time period when either the customer or agent was interrupting the other person.

Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html#/c:objc(c.name: nonTalkTimeFilter
Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html#/c:objc(c.abstract: A condition for a time period when neither the customer nor the agent was talking.

Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html#/c:objc(c.name: sentimentFilter
Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html#/c:objc(c.abstract: A condition that is applied to a particular customer sentiment.

Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html#/c:objc(c.name: transcriptFilter
Classes/AWSTranscribeRule.html#/c:objc(c.abstract: A condition that catches particular words or phrases based on a exact match. For example, if you set the phrase “I want to speak to the manager”, only that exact phrase will be returned.

Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.name: endPercentage
Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.abstract:
A value that indicates the percentage of the end of the time range. To set a relative time range, you must specify a start percentage and an end percentage. For example, if you specify the following values:

  • StartPercentage - 10

  • EndPercentage - 50

This looks at the time range starting from 10% of the way into the call to 50% of the way through the call. For a call that lasts 100,000 milliseconds, this example range would apply from the 10,000 millisecond mark to the 50,000 millisecond mark.

Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.name: first
Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.abstract: A range that takes the portion of the call up to the time in milliseconds set by the value that you’ve specified. For example, if you specify 120000, the time range is set for the first 120,000 milliseconds of the call.

Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.name: last
Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.abstract: A range that takes the portion of the call from the time in milliseconds set by the value that you’ve specified to the end of the call. For example, if you specify 120000, the time range is set for the last 120,000 milliseconds of the call.

Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.name: startPercentage
Classes/AWSTranscribeRelativeTimeRange.h.abstract:
A value that indicates the percentage of the beginning of the time range. To set a relative time range, you must specify a start percentage and an end percentage. For example, if you specify the following values:

  • StartPercentage - 10

  • EndPercentage - 50

This looks at the time range starting from 10% of the way into the call to 50% of the way through the call. For a call that lasts 100,000 milliseconds, this example range would apply from the 10,000 millisecond mark to the 50,000 millisecond mark.

Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.name: absoluteTimeRange
Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.abstract: An object you can use to specify a time range (in milliseconds) for when no one is talking. For example, you could specify a time period between the 30,000 millisecond mark and the 45,000 millisecond mark. You could also specify the time period as the first 15,000 milliseconds or the last 15,000 milliseconds.

Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.name: negate
Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.abstract: Set to TRUE to look for a time period when people were talking.

Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.name: relativeTimeRange
Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.abstract: An object that allows percentages to specify the proportion of the call where there was silence. For example, you can specify the first half of the call. You can also specify the period of time between halfway through to three-quarters of the way through the call. Because the length of conversation can vary between calls, you can apply relative time ranges across all calls.

Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.name: threshold
Classes/AWSTranscribeNonTalkTimeFilter.h.abstract: The duration of the period when neither the customer nor agent was talking.

Amazon Transcribe Medical also produces a transcription of each item detected on an audio channel, including the start time and end time of the item and alternative transcriptions of item. The alternative transcriptions also come with confidence scores provided by Amazon Transcribe Medical.

You can’t set both ShowSpeakerLabels and ChannelIdentification in the same request. If you set both, your request returns a BadRequestException.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: maxAlternatives

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract: The maximum number of speakers to identify in the input audio. If there are more speakers in the audio than this number, multiple speakers are identified as a single speaker. If you specify the MaxSpeakerLabels field, you must set the ShowSpeakerLabels field to true.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: showAlternatives
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract: Determines whether alternative transcripts are generated along with the transcript that has the highest confidence. If you set ShowAlternatives field to true, you must also set the maximum number of alternatives to return in the MaxAlternatives field.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: showSpeakerLabels
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract:
Determines whether the transcription job uses speaker recognition to identify different speakers in the input audio. Speaker recognition labels individual speakers in the audio file. If you set the ShowSpeakerLabels field to true, you must also set the maximum number of speaker labels in the MaxSpeakerLabels field.

You can’t set both ShowSpeakerLabels and ChannelIdentification in the same request. If you set both, your request returns a BadRequestException.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: contentIdentificationType
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract: Shows the type of content that you’ve configured Amazon Transcribe Medical to identify in a transcription job. If the value is PHI, you’ve configured the job to identify personal health information (PHI) in the transcription output.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: creationTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job was created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract:
If the TranscriptionJobStatus field is FAILED, this field contains information about why the job failed.

The FailureReason field contains one of the following values:

  • Unsupported media format- The media format specified in the MediaFormat field of the request isn’t valid. See the description of the MediaFormat field for a list of valid values.

  • The media format provided does not match the detected media format- The media format of the audio file doesn’t match the format specified in the MediaFormat field in the request. Check the media format of your media file and make sure the two values match.

  • Invalid sample rate for audio file- The sample rate specified in the MediaSampleRateHertz of the request isn’t valid. The sample rate must be between 8,000 and 48,000 Hertz.

  • The sample rate provided does not match the detected sample rate- The sample rate in the audio file doesn’t match the sample rate specified in the MediaSampleRateHertz field in the request. Check the sample rate of your media file and make sure that the two values match.

  • Invalid file size: file size too large- The size of your audio file is larger than what Amazon Transcribe Medical can process. For more information, see Guidelines and Quotas in the Amazon Transcribe Medical Guide.

  • Invalid number of channels: number of channels too large- Your audio contains more channels than Amazon Transcribe Medical is configured to process. To request additional channels, see Amazon Transcribe Medical Endpoints and Quotas in the Amazon Web Services General Reference.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract: The language code for the language spoken in the source audio file. US English (en-US) is the only supported language for medical transcriptions. Any other value you enter for language code results in a BadRequestException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: mediaFormat
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.abstract: The format of the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedicalTranscriptio.name: mediaSampleRateHertz

If you don’t specify the sample rate, Amazon Transcribe Medical determines it for you. If you choose to specify the sample rate, it must match the rate detected by Amazon Transcribe Medical.

If there are more language models in the list than the page size, Amazon Transcribe returns the NextPage token. Include the token in the next request to the operation to return the next page of language models.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListLanguageModelsR.name: maxResults
Classes/AWSTranscribeListLanguageModelsR.abstract: The maximum number of language models to return in each page of results. If there are fewer results than the value you specify, only the actual results are returned. If you do not specify a value, the default of 5 is used.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListLanguageModelsR.name: nameContains
Classes/AWSTranscribeListLanguageModelsR.abstract: When specified, the custom language model names returned contain the substring you’ve specified.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListLanguageModelsR.name: nextToken
Classes/AWSTranscribeListLanguageModelsR.abstract: When included, fetches the next set of jobs if the result of the previous request was truncated.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListLanguageModelsR.name: statusEquals
Classes/AWSTranscribeListLanguageModelsR.abstract: When specified, returns only custom language models with the specified status. Language models are ordered by creation date, with the newest models first. If you don’t specify a status, Amazon Transcribe returns all custom language models ordered by date.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.name: callAnalyticsJobSummaries
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.abstract: A list of objects containing summary information for a transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.name: nextToken
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.abstract: The operation returns a page of jobs at a time. The maximum size of the page is set by the MaxResults parameter. If there are more jobs in the list than the page size, Amazon Transcribe returns the NextPage token. Include the token in your next request to the operation to return next page of jobs.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.name: status
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.abstract: When specified, returns only call analytics jobs with that status. Jobs are ordered by creation date, with the most recent jobs returned first. If you don’t specify a status, Amazon Transcribe returns all transcription jobs ordered by creation date.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.name: jobNameContains
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.abstract: When specified, the jobs returned in the list are limited to jobs whose name contains the specified string.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.name: maxResults
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.abstract: The maximum number of call analytics jobs to return in each page of results. If there are fewer results than the value you specify, only the actual results are returned. If you do not specify a value, the default of 5 is used.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.name: nextToken
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.abstract: If you receive a truncated result in the previous request of , include NextToken to fetch the next set of jobs.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.name: status
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsJo.abstract: When specified, returns only call analytics jobs with the specified status. Jobs are ordered by creation date, with the most recent jobs returned first. If you don’t specify a status, Amazon Transcribe returns all analytics jobs ordered by creation date.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsCa.name: categories
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsCa.abstract: A list of objects containing information about analytics categories.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsCa.name: nextToken
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsCa.abstract: The operation returns a page of jobs at a time. The maximum size of the list is set by the MaxResults parameter. If there are more categories in the list than the page size, Amazon Transcribe returns the NextPage token. Include the token in the next request to the operation to return the next page of analytics categories.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsCa.name: maxResults
Classes/AWSTranscribeListCallAnalyticsCa.abstract: The maximum number of categories to return in each page of results. If there are fewer results than the value you specify, only the actual results are returned. If you do not specify a value, the default of 5 is used.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.name: baseModelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.abstract: The Amazon Transcribe standard language model, or base model used to create the custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.name: createTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.abstract: The time the custom language model was created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.abstract: The reason why the custom language model couldn’t be created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.name: inputDataConfig
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.abstract: The data access role and Amazon S3 prefixes for the input files used to train the custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.abstract: The language code you used to create your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.abstract: The most recent time the custom language model was modified.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.name: modelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.abstract: The name of the custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.name: modelStatus
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.abstract: The creation status of a custom language model. When the status is COMPLETED the model is ready for use.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.name: upgradeAvailability
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageModel.html#.abstract: Whether the base model used for the custom language model is up to date. If this field is true then you are running the most up-to-date version of the base model in your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageIdSettings..name: languageModelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageIdSettings..abstract: The name of the language model you want to use when transcribing your audio. The model you specify must have the same language codes as the transcription job; if the languages don’t match, the language model isn’t be applied.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageIdSettings..name: vocabularyFilterName
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageIdSettings..abstract: The name of the vocabulary filter you want to use when transcribing your audio. The filter you specify must have the same language codes as the transcription job; if the languages don’t match, the vocabulary filter isn’t be applied.

Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageIdSettings..name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeLanguageIdSettings..abstract: The name of the vocabulary you want to use when processing your transcription job. The vocabulary you specify must have the same language codes as the transcription job; if the languages don’t match, the vocabulary isn’t applied.

Classes/AWSTranscribeJobExecutionSetting.name: allowDeferredExecution
Classes/AWSTranscribeJobExecutionSetting.abstract:
Indicates whether a job should be queued by Amazon Transcribe when the concurrent execution limit is exceeded. When the AllowDeferredExecution field is true, jobs are queued and executed when the number of executing jobs falls below the concurrent execution limit. If the field is false, Amazon Transcribe returns a LimitExceededException exception.

Note that job queuing is enabled by default for call analytics jobs.

If you specify the AllowDeferredExecution field, you must specify the DataAccessRoleArn field.

Classes/AWSTranscribeJobExecutionSetting.name: dataAccessRoleArn
Classes/AWSTranscribeJobExecutionSetting.abstract:
The Amazon Resource Name (ARN), in the form arn:partition:service:region:account-id:resource-type/resource-id, of a role that has access to the S3 bucket that contains the input files. Amazon Transcribe assumes this role to read queued media files. If you have specified an output S3 bucket for the transcription results, this role should have access to the output bucket as well.

If you specify the AllowDeferredExecution field, you must specify the DataAccessRoleArn field.

Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..name: absoluteTimeRange
Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..abstract: An object you can use to specify a time range (in milliseconds) for when you’d want to find the interruption. For example, you could search for an interruption between the 30,000 millisecond mark and the 45,000 millisecond mark. You could also specify the time period as the first 15,000 milliseconds or the last 15,000 milliseconds.

Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..name: negate
Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..abstract: Set to TRUE to look for a time period where there was no interruption.

Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..name: participantRole
Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..abstract: Indicates whether the caller or customer was interrupting.

Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..name: relativeTimeRange
Classes/AWSTranscribeInterruptionFilter..abstract: An object that allows percentages to specify the proportion of the call where there was a interruption. For example, you can specify the first half of the call. You can also specify the period of time between halfway through to three-quarters of the way through the call. Because the length of conversation can vary between calls, you can apply relative time ranges across all calls.

Classes/AWSTranscribeInputDataConfig.htm.name: dataAccessRoleArn
Classes/AWSTranscribeInputDataConfig.htm.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) that uniquely identifies the permissions you’ve given Amazon Transcribe to access your Amazon S3 buckets containing your media files or text data. ARNs have the format arn:partition:service:region:account-id:resource-type/resource-id.

Classes/AWSTranscribeInputDataConfig.htm.name: s3Uri
Classes/AWSTranscribeInputDataConfig.htm.abstract: The Amazon S3 prefix you specify to access the plain text files that you use to train your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeInputDataConfig.htm.name: tuningDataS3Uri
Classes/AWSTranscribeInputDataConfig.htm.abstract: The Amazon S3 prefix you specify to access the plain text files that you use to tune your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: downloadUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: The S3 location where the vocabulary is stored. Use this URI to get the contents of the vocabulary. The URI is available for a limited time.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: If the VocabularyState field is FAILED, this field contains information about why the job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: The language code of the vocabulary entries.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: The date and time that the vocabulary was last modified.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: The name of the vocabulary to return.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyReques.name: vocabularyName

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyFilter.name: downloadUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyFilter.abstract: The URI of the list of words in the vocabulary filter. You can use this URI to get the list of words.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyFilter.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyFilter.abstract: The language code of the words in the vocabulary filter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyFilter.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyFilter.abstract: The date and time that the contents of the vocabulary filter were updated.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyFilter.name: vocabularyFilterName
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyFilter.abstract: The name of the vocabulary filter for which to return information.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetTranscriptionJob.name: transcriptionJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetTranscriptionJob.abstract: An object that contains the results of the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.name: downloadUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.abstract: The location in Amazon S3 where the vocabulary is stored. Use this URI to get the contents of the vocabulary. You can download your vocabulary from the URI for a limited time.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.abstract: If the VocabularyState is FAILED, this field contains information about why the job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.abstract: The valid language code for your vocabulary entries.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.abstract: The date and time that the vocabulary was last modified with a text file different from the one that was previously used.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.abstract: The name of the vocabulary returned by Amazon Transcribe Medical.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.name: vocabularyState
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.abstract: The processing state of the vocabulary. If the VocabularyState is READY then you can use it in the StartMedicalTranscriptionJob operation.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalVocabular.abstract: The name of the vocabulary that you want information about. The value is case sensitive.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalTranscrip.name: medicalTranscriptionJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalTranscrip.abstract: An object that contains the results of the medical transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalTranscrip.name: medicalTranscriptionJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetMedicalTranscrip.abstract: The name of the medical transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetCallAnalyticsJob.name: callAnalyticsJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetCallAnalyticsJob.abstract: An object that contains the results of your call analytics job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetCallAnalyticsJob.name: callAnalyticsJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetCallAnalyticsJob.abstract: The name of the analytics job you want information about. This value is case sensitive.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetCallAnalyticsCat.name: categoryProperties
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetCallAnalyticsCat.abstract: The rules you’ve defined for a category.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetCallAnalyticsCat.name: categoryName
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetCallAnalyticsCat.abstract: The name of the category you want information about. This value is case sensitive.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDescribeLanguageMod.name: languageModel
Classes/AWSTranscribeDescribeLanguageMod.abstract: The name of the custom language model you requested more information about.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDescribeLanguageMod.name: modelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDescribeLanguageMod.abstract: The name of the custom language model you submit to get more information.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteVocabularyReq.abstract: The name of the vocabulary to delete.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteVocabularyFil.name: vocabularyFilterName

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteTranscription.name: transcriptionJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteTranscription.abstract: The name of the transcription job to be deleted.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteMedicalVocabu.abstract: The name of the vocabulary that you want to delete.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteMedicalTransc.name: medicalTranscriptionJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteMedicalTransc.abstract: The name you provide to the DeleteMedicalTranscriptionJob object to delete a transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteLanguageModel.name: modelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteLanguageModel.abstract: The name of the model you’re choosing to delete.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteCallAnalytics.name: callAnalyticsJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteCallAnalytics.abstract: The name of the call analytics job you want to delete.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteCallAnalytics.name: categoryName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteCallAnalytics.abstract: The name of the call analytics category that you’re choosing to delete. The value is case sensitive.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.abstract: If the VocabularyState field is FAILED, this field contains information about why the job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.abstract: The language code of the vocabulary entries.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.abstract: The date and time that the vocabulary was created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.name: vocabularyState
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.abstract: The processing state of the vocabulary. When the VocabularyState field contains READY the vocabulary is ready to be used in a StartTranscriptionJob request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract: The language code of the vocabulary entries. For a list of languages and their corresponding language codes, see table-language-matrix.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: phrases
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract: An array of strings that contains the vocabulary entries.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract: Adds one or more tags, each in the form of a key:value pair, to a new Amazon Transcribe vocabulary at the time you create this new vocabulary.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract:
The S3 location of the text file that contains the definition of the custom vocabulary. The URI must be in the same region as the API endpoint that you are calling. The general form is:

https://s3.<Amazon Web Services-region>.amazonaws.com/<AWSDOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET>/<keyprefix>/<objectkey>

For example:

https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/AWSDOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET/vocab.txt

For more information about S3 object names, see Object Keys in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

For more information about custom vocabularies, see Custom vocabularies.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract: The name of the vocabulary. The name must be unique within an Amazon Web Services account. The name is case sensitive. If you try to create a vocabulary with the same name as a previous vocabulary you will receive a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract: The language code of the words in the collection.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract: The date and time that the vocabulary filter was modified.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract: The language code of the words in the vocabulary filter. All words in the filter must be in the same language. The vocabulary filter can only be used with transcription jobs in the specified language.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract: Adds one or more tags, each in the form of a key:value pair, to a new Amazon Transcribe vocabulary filter at the time you create this new vocabulary filter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: vocabularyFilterFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract:
The Amazon S3 location of a text file used as input to create the vocabulary filter. Only use characters from the character set defined for custom vocabularies. For a list of character sets, see Character Sets for Custom Vocabularies.

The specified file must be less than 50 KB of UTF-8 characters.

If you provide the location of a list of words in the VocabularyFilterFileUri parameter, you can’t use the Words parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: vocabularyFilterName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract: The vocabulary filter name. The name must be unique within the account that contains it. If you try to create a vocabulary filter with the same name as another vocabulary filter, you get a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.name: words
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyFil.abstract:
The words to use in the vocabulary filter. Only use characters from the character set defined for custom vocabularies. For a list of character sets, see Character Sets for Custom Vocabularies.

If you provide a list of words in the Words parameter, you can’t use the VocabularyFilterFileUri parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: If the VocabularyState field is FAILED, this field contains information about why the job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The language code for the entries in your custom vocabulary. US English (en-US) is the only valid language code for Amazon Transcribe Medical.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The date and time that you created the vocabulary.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The name of the vocabulary. The name must be unique within an Amazon Web Services account and is case sensitive.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyState
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The processing state of your custom vocabulary in Amazon Transcribe Medical. If the state is READY, you can use the vocabulary in a StartMedicalTranscriptionJob request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The language code for the language used for the entries in your custom vocabulary. The language code of your custom vocabulary must match the language code of your transcription job. US English (en-US) is the only language code available for Amazon Transcribe Medical.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: Adds one or more tags, each in the form of a key:value pair, to a new medical vocabulary at the time you create this new vocabulary.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract:
The location in Amazon S3 of the text file you use to define your custom vocabulary. The URI must be in the same Amazon Web Services Region as the resource that you’re calling. Enter information about your VocabularyFileUri in the following format:

https://s3.<aws-region>.amazonaws.com/<bucket-name>/<keyprefix>/<objectkey>

The following is an example URI for a vocabulary file that is stored in Amazon S3:

https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/AWSDOC-EXAMPLE-BUCKET/vocab.txt

For more information about Amazon S3 object names, see Object Keys in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

For more information about custom vocabularies, see Medical Custom Vocabularies.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateMedicalVocabu.abstract: The name of the custom vocabulary. This case-sensitive name must be unique within an Amazon Web Services account. If you try to create a vocabulary with the same name as a previous vocabulary, you get a ConflictException error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: baseModelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The Amazon Transcribe standard language model, or base model you’ve used to create a custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: inputDataConfig
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The data access role and Amazon S3 prefixes you’ve chosen to create your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The language code of the text you’ve used to create a custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: modelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The name you’ve chosen for your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: modelStatus
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The status of the custom language model. When the status is COMPLETED the model is ready to use.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: baseModelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract:
The Amazon Transcribe standard language model, or base model used to create your custom language model.

If you want to use your custom language model to transcribe audio with a sample rate of 16,000 Hz or greater, choose Wideband.

If you want to use your custom language model to transcribe audio with a sample rate that is less than 16,000 Hz, choose Narrowband.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: inputDataConfig
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: Contains the data access role and the Amazon S3 prefixes to read the required input files to create a custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The language of the input text you’re using to train your custom language model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: modelName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: The name you choose for your custom language model when you create it.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.name: tags
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateLanguageModel.abstract: Adds one or more tags, each in the form of a key:value pair, to a new language model at the time you create this new model.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.name: categoryProperties
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.abstract: The rules and associated metadata used to create a category.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.name: categoryName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.abstract: The name that you choose for your category when you create it.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.name: rules
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateCallAnalytics.abstract: To create a category, you must specify between 1 and 20 rules. For each rule, you specify a filter to be applied to the attributes of the call. For example, you can specify a sentiment filter to detect if the customer’s sentiment was negative or neutral.

Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.name: piiEntityTypes
Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.abstract: The types of personally identifiable information (PII) you want to redact in your transcript.

Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.name: redactionOutput
Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.abstract:
The output transcript file stored in either the default S3 bucket or in a bucket you specify.

When you choose redacted Amazon Transcribe outputs only the redacted transcript.

When you choose redacted_and_unredacted Amazon Transcribe outputs both the redacted and unredacted transcripts.

Classes/AWSTranscribeContentRedaction.ht.name: redactionType

Classes/AWSTranscribeChannelDefinition.h.name: participantRole

Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..abstract: The name of the call analytics category.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..name: lastUpdateTime

Classes/AWSTranscribeCategoryProperties..name: rules

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract: The name of the call analytics job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract: The status of the call analytics job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: completionTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job was completed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: creationTime

Classes/AWSTranscribeCallAnalyticsJobSum.name: startTime
